+## Recommended Approach
+
+**Recommendation**: Four pure modules in `src/core/` (`reducer.ts`, `move.ts`,
+`winCheck.ts`, `history.ts`) plus one tiny shared helper `src/core/coordKey.ts`, backed by
+extended types in `src/types.ts`. `GameState` is immutable and shallow-copied per
+transition; `static` is reused by reference. A `coordKey(c: Coord): string` helper
+reconciles `Set<Coord>` referential equality with the structural membership tests that
+`winCheck` and `move` require. `reducer(state, intent)` stays a pure 2-arg function by
+carrying an immutable `initial` snapshot on `GameState` (a necessary, minimal extension of
+D3's locked shape). `AnimSpec` is emitted on every successful move with `from`/`to` = the
+**player's** previous→current coords and `entities` listing `'player'` plus the pushed box
+index when applicable; the ph.5 animator derives each entity's visual segment from the
+shared move delta. Undo and reset snap (no anim), and `won` is recomputed via `winCheck` on
+every transition (move, undo, reset). All core tests live in `tests/unit/core/` and run
+under the `unit` Vitest project (node env). **Confidence: HIGH** on the overall shape;
+per-item confidence is labeled inline.
+
+**Rationale**: This is the simulation layer — every acceptance-critical rule (move
+validity, push, win, undo, reset boundary) lives here and must be testable without a DOM.
+The four-module split matches D1 and the architecture's "no god-objects" boundary. The
+`coordKey` helper is the single correction the locked `Set<Coord>` shape needs to be
+*correct* without amending D3's type: `Set<Coord>` stays the storage type (matching the
+architecture diagram), and the lookup functions derive a `Set<string>` per call — O(W) or
+O(T) per move, trivial at ≤ ~225 walls / ≤ 30 targets. Carrying `initial` on `GameState`
+is the only way to keep `reducer` a pure 2-arg function (the alternative is a
+`createReducer` factory, which changes the export shape the assignment pins down). Defining
+`AnimSpec` now per D8 lets ph.5 plug in without a reducer signature change; interpreting
+`from`/`to` as the player's segment with a shared delta is the cleanest reading that fits
+the locked shape and handles pushes. Recomputing `won` on undo/reset (not only on move) is
+the mitigation for pitfalls BLOCKER #3 and MAJOR #17 — a pushed-then-undone box must clear
+`won`, and reset must clear the undo stack.
