+### `src/core/coordKey.ts` — shared helper (HIGH)
+
+A fifth file beyond D1's four (`reducer`, `move`, `winCheck`, `history`). D1 lists the four
+*rule* modules; `coordKey` is a leaf utility shared by `move` and `winCheck` (importing it
+from either would create a needless cross-rule-module dependency). The alternative —
+duplicating the one-liner in both files — is worse than a 4-line shared file. Recommended.
+
+```ts
+import type { Coord } from '../types';
+
+/** Structural key for `Coord`. Use for `Set`/`Map` membership where `Set<Coord>` would
+ *  fall back to object identity. Format: `"x,y"` (e.g. `{x:3,y:7}` -> `"3,7"`). */
+export function coordKey(c: Coord): string {
+  return `${c.x},${c.y}`;
+}
+```
+
+### `src/core/winCheck.ts` (HIGH)
+
+```ts
+import type { GameState } from '../types';
+import { coordKey } from './coordKey';
+
+/**
+ * O(B + T) per call. `B` = boxes.length, `T` = targets.size (≤ ~30 each).
+ * Builds a string-keyed set from `state.static.targets` per call to defeat `Set<Coord>`
+ * object identity. Cheap and exact; no incremental counter (architecture: Win-check).
+ */
+export function winCheck(state: GameState): boolean {
+  if (state.boxes.length !== state.static.targets.size) return false;
+  const targetKeys = new Set<string>();
+  for (const t of state.static.targets) targetKeys.add(coordKey(t));
+  return state.boxes.every((b) => targetKeys.has(coordKey(b)));
+}
+```
+
+**Why the per-call `Set<string>` rebuild?** `state.static.targets` is a `Set<Coord>` (D3
+lock). A box pushed onto a target is a *fresh* `Coord` object (`{ x: bx + dx, y: by + dy }`),
+so `state.static.targets.has(freshBox)` returns `false` even when the box is structurally on
+a target. Building `targetKeys: Set<string>` once per `winCheck` call restores structural
+equality. Rebuild cost is O(T) ≤ ~30 — negligible. `static` itself is never mutated. **HIGH.**
+
+### `src/core/move.ts` (HIGH)
+
+```ts
+import type { Coord, Direction, GameState } from '../types';
+import { coordKey } from './coordKey';
+
+/** Result of a successful move. `null` means the move was invalid (wall or blocked box). */
+export interface MoveResult {
+  /** New player position. */
+  player: Coord;
+  /** New boxes array. A fresh array ONLY when a box was pushed; otherwise the SAME
+   *  reference as `state.boxes` (no allocation on a pure walk — the reducer still
+   *  shallow-copies for its own output, but `move` itself doesn't). */
+  boxes: Coord[];
+  /** Index of the pushed box, if this move was a push. */
+  pushedIndex?: number;
+  /** Previous position of the pushed box, if this move was a push. */
+  boxFrom?: Coord;
+}
+
+/** Direction → tile delta. y increases downward (screen/canvas convention). */
+const DELTA: Record<Direction, Coord> = {
+  N: { x: 0, y: -1 },
+  S: { x: 0, y: 1 },
+  E: { x: 1, y: 0 },
+  W: { x: -1, y: 0 },
+};
+
+/**
+ * Attempt to move the player one tile in `dir`. Pushes a box if the destination is
+ * occupied by a box and the tile beyond it is floor/target (not wall, not another box).
+ * Returns `null` for an invalid move (into a wall, or into a box that cannot be pushed).
+ * PURE: does not mutate `state`; reads only.
+ */
+export function move(state: GameState, dir: Direction): MoveResult | null {
+  const d = DELTA[dir];
+  const next: Coord = { x: state.player.x + d.x, y: state.player.y + d.y };
+
+  // Wall check (structural via coordKey).
+  const wallKeys = new Set<string>();
+  for (const w of state.static.walls) wallKeys.add(coordKey(w));
+  if (wallKeys.has(coordKey(next))) return null;
+
+  // Is there a box at `next`? (index search; ≤ ~30 boxes)
+  const boxIndex = state.boxes.findIndex((b) => b.x === next.x && b.y === next.y);
+  if (boxIndex === -1) {
+    // Pure walk.
+    return { player: next, boxes: state.boxes };
+  }
+
+  // Push: check the tile beyond the box.
+  const beyond: Coord = { x: next.x + d.x, y: next.y + d.y };
+  if (wallKeys.has(coordKey(beyond))) return null;          // blocked by wall
+  if (state.boxes.some((b) => b.x === beyond.x && b.y === beyond.y)) return null; // by box
+
+  const boxFrom = state.boxes[boxIndex]; // Coord | undefined under noUncheckedIndexedAccess
+  if (boxFrom === undefined) return null; // defensive; index came from findIndex so safe
+
+  const newBoxes = state.boxes.slice();
+  newBoxes[boxIndex] = beyond;
+  return { player: next, boxes: newBoxes, pushedIndex: boxIndex, boxFrom };
+}
+```
+
+**Notes:**
+- `DELTA` uses the standard screen convention (y down). Tests assert this explicitly. **HIGH.**
+- `wallKeys` is rebuilt per call (O(W) ≤ ~225). Alternative: cache on `state.static` —
+  rejected, it would mean mutating `static` (violates the referential-equality invariant)
+  or adding a parallel `Set<string>` field to `static` (bloats D3's locked shape). Per-call
+  rebuild is simpler and cheap. **HIGH.**
+- `boxes` array is only copied on a push; a pure walk returns the *same* `boxes` reference.
+  The reducer still produces a new `GameState`, but `move` itself avoids one allocation on
+  walks. **MEDIUM** — micro-optimization; the executor may simplify to always-copy if it
+  reads cleaner. Flagged as a REFACTOR-stage decision.
+- `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`: `state.boxes[boxIndex]` is `Coord | undefined`; guarded with
+  an explicit `undefined` check even though `findIndex` guarantees the index is valid. This
+  satisfies the compiler without a non-null assertion. **HIGH.**
+- `findIndex` / `some` use structural `x`/`y` comparison directly (not `coordKey`) — fine
+  for a linear scan; `coordKey` is only needed for `Set` membership.
+
+### `src/core/history.ts` (HIGH)
+
+```ts
+import type { GameState, HistoryEntry } from '../types';
+
+/** Push `entry` onto the undo stack. Returns a NEW state with `history` shallow-copied
+ *  (append); all other fields shared by reference. Does NOT mutate `state`. */
+export function pushEntry(state: GameState, entry: HistoryEntry): GameState {
+  return { ...state, history: [...state.history, entry] };
+}
+
+/** Pop the top entry off the undo stack. Returns `null` if the stack is empty.
+ *  The returned `state` has the entry REMOVED from `history` but positions are NOT
+ *  restored — the reducer's `undo` branch reads `entry` and restores player/box/moveCount
+ *  itself, then recomputes `won`. This keeps `history.ts` as pure stack mechanics. */
+export function popEntry(
+  state: GameState,
+): { state: GameState; entry: HistoryEntry } | null {
+  if (state.history.length === 0) return null;
+  const entry = state.history[state.history.length - 1]; // HistoryEntry | undefined
+  if (entry === undefined) return null; // defensive under noUncheckedIndexedAccess
+  const history = state.history.slice(0, -1);
+  return { state: { ...state, history }, entry };
+}
+
+/** Clear the undo stack entirely (reset = hard boundary per D6 / MAJOR #17).
+ *  Returns a NEW state with `history: []`. */
+export function clearHistory(state: GameState): GameState {
+  return { ...state, history: [] };
+}
+```
+
+**Note on the pop/restore split:** `popEntry` only removes the entry; the *semantic* restore
+(player/box/moveCount) is the reducer's job. This avoids duplicating the restore logic and
+keeps `history.ts` trivially testable as pure stack operations. The reducer's `undo` branch
+is the single place that interprets a `HistoryEntry`. **HIGH.**
+
+### `src/core/reducer.ts` (HIGH)
+
+```ts
+import type { AnimSpec, GameState, Intent, Level } from '../types';
+import { move } from './move';
+import { winCheck } from './winCheck';
+import { pushEntry, popEntry, clearHistory } from './history';
+
+/** Move tween duration (ms). Constant for ph.2; ph.5 animator consumes this.
+ *  Exported so tests can assert `anim.duration` without a magic number. */
+export const MOVE_DURATION_MS = 120;
+
+export interface ReducerResult {
+  state: GameState;
+  /** Present on a successful `move`; absent on `undo`, `reset`, and no-op moves. */
+  anim?: AnimSpec;
+}
+
+/** Build the initial `GameState` from a `Level`. Used by ph.3 loader and by tests. */
+export function createInitialState(level: Level): GameState {
+  const initial = { player: level.player, boxes: level.boxes.slice() };
+  return {
+    levelId: level.id,
+    static: {
+      width: level.width,
+      height: level.height,
+      walls: level.walls,
+      targets: level.targets,
+    },
+    initial,
+    player: level.player,
+    boxes: level.boxes.slice(),
+    moveCount: 0,
+    history: [],
+    won: winCheck({ boxes: level.boxes, static: { targets: level.targets } } as GameState),
+  };
+}
+
+/** Pure reducer. `reset` reads `state.initial` (immutable, shared by ref). */
+export function reducer(state: GameState, intent: Intent): ReducerResult {
+  switch (intent.type) {
+    case 'move': {
+      const result = move(state, intent.dir);
+      if (result === null) return { state }; // invalid: same ref, no anim (D7)
+
+      const entry = {
+        player: state.player,
+        pushedBoxIndex: result.pushedIndex,
+        boxFrom: result.boxFrom,
+        moveCount: state.moveCount,
+      };
+      const moved = pushEntry(state, entry);
+      const next: GameState = {
+        ...moved,
+        player: result.player,
+        boxes: result.boxes,
+        moveCount: state.moveCount + 1,
+      };
+      next.won = winCheck(next);
+      const anim: AnimSpec = {
+        from: state.player,
+        to: result.player,
+        duration: MOVE_DURATION_MS,
+        entities:
+          result.pushedIndex === undefined
+            ? ['player']
+            : ['player', result.pushedIndex],
+      };
+      return { state: next, anim };
+    }
+
+    case 'undo': {
+      const popped = popEntry(state);
+      if (popped === null) return { state }; // empty stack: same ref, no anim
+
+      const { state: poppedState, entry } = popped;
+      // Restore positions from the entry.
+      let boxes = poppedState.boxes;
+      if (entry.pushedBoxIndex !== undefined && entry.boxFrom !== undefined) {
+        const idx = entry.pushedBoxIndex;
+        const from = entry.boxFrom;
+        boxes = poppedState.boxes.map((b, i) => (i === idx ? from : b));
+      }
+      const restored: GameState = {
+        ...poppedState,
+        player: entry.player,
+        boxes,
+        moveCount: entry.moveCount,
+      };
+      restored.won = winCheck(restored);
+      return { state: restored }; // no anim on undo (D8)
+    }
+
+    case 'reset': {
+      const cleared = clearHistory(state);
+      const fresh: GameState = {
+        ...cleared,
+        player: state.initial.player,
+        boxes: state.initial.boxes.slice(),
+        moveCount: 0,
+      };
+      fresh.won = winCheck(fresh);
+      return { state: fresh }; // no anim on reset (D8)
+    }
+  }
+}
+```
+
+**Notes:**
+- `MOVE_DURATION_MS = 120` is a constant exported from `reducer.ts`. Rationale: ph.2 has no
+  config system; a constant is the simplest thing that lets tests assert `anim.duration`
+  without a magic number and lets ph.5 import it. ph.9 may lift it to a config if tuning is
+  needed. **HIGH** on constant-now; **MEDIUM** on the exact value (120 ms is within the
+  NFR-5 100–150 ms band; ph.5 may tune). See Pitfalls.
+- `createInitialState` computes `won` once via a minimal-shape `GameState` cast. This is the
+  only slightly awkward spot; the alternative is to inline the winCheck logic
+  (`level.boxes.every(b => targetKeys.has(coordKey(b)))`) — but that duplicates `winCheck`.
+  The `as GameState` cast is contained to this one factory. **MEDIUM** — the executor may
+  prefer to build the full state first and then call `winCheck(state)` to set `won` (cleaner;
+  avoids the cast). Recommended for the executor: construct `state` fully with `won: false`,
+  then `state.won = winCheck(state)` before returning. This removes the cast entirely.
+- `noFallthroughCasesInSwitch` is satisfied: each `case` returns. The switch is exhaustive
+  over `Intent` (`'move' | 'undo' | 'reset'`), so no default is needed. **HIGH.**
+- Invalid move returns the **same** `state` reference (`{ state }`), enabling `===` checks
+  in tests and callers (D7). Undo on empty stack likewise returns the same ref. **HIGH.**
+- `static` is never copied (spread `{ ...moved }` / `{ ...cleared }` copies the *reference*
+  to `static`), satisfying the referential-equality invariant. **HIGH.**
