+## Alternatives Considered
+
+| Approach | Pros | Cons | Verdict |
+|----------|------|------|---------|
+| **`Set<Coord>` + per-call `coordKey` rebuild** (recommended) | Respects D3's locked `Set<Coord>` type; correct structural equality; O(W)/O(T) per call is trivial at this scale; `static` stays a plain `Set<Coord>` matching the architecture diagram | Rebuilds a `Set<string>` on every `move`/`winCheck` call (≤ ~225 + ~30 entries — nanoseconds) | **Adopt.** *(HIGH)* |
+| `Set<string>` for `walls`/`targets` from the start (keyed by `coordKey`) | No per-call rebuild; membership is O(1) structural | Violates D3's locked `Set<Coord>` shape — requires a `context.md` amendment; loses the `Coord` object on readback (must parse the string) | Rejected for ph.2 (would re-open a locked decision). *(HIGH on correctness, but out of scope.)* |
+| `Map<string, Coord>` keyed by `coordKey` | O(1) structural lookup AND keeps the `Coord` value | Heavier than needed; `Set<Coord>` + `coordKey` rebuild is simpler at this scale | Rejected. *(HIGH)* |
+| Intern `Coord` objects (one canonical instance per tile) | `Set<Coord>#has` works referentially; no `coordKey` needed | Requires an interning registry; pushes a box's new coord must be canonicalized post-push — fragile and surprising; violates "boxes are plain data" | Rejected. *(HIGH)* |
+| `createReducer(initialState)` factory (closures over initial) | `GameState` stays exactly D3's shape (no `initial` field); reset reads the closed-over initial | Changes the export from `reducer(state, intent)` to a factory-returned function — breaks the assignment's pinned signature; tests must call `const r = createReducer(init)` first | Rejected as primary; documented as the cleanest alternative if the planner prefers to keep `GameState` minimal. *(MEDIUM)* |
+| `initial` stored inside `static` | Keeps `initial` grouped with level-derived data | `static` is structural (walls/targets/dimensions); player/boxes start positions are not structural — misleading grouping | Rejected. *(MEDIUM)* |
+| `popEntry` applies the restore (returns fully-restored state) | Reducer `undo` branch is one line | Splits undo semantics across `history.ts` and `reducer.ts`; `history.ts` must know about `won` recompute or leave it stale | Rejected. *(HIGH)* |
+| `AnimSpec` with per-entity `from`/`to` map | Fully precise for pushes | Violates D8's locked `{ from, to, duration, entities }` shape; requires a context amendment | Rejected for ph.2. Documented as a ph.5 refinement option if the shared-delta interpretation proves insufficient. *(MEDIUM)* |
+| `boxesOnTargets(state): Set<number>` in ph.2 | Renderer (ph.3) will need it | The *renderer* needs it, not the core; core's job is `won: boolean` via `winCheck`. Defining it now is YAGNI. | Deferred to ph.3. *(HIGH)* |
+
+---
+
+## Known Pitfalls
+
+### P1: `Set<Coord>` uses object identity — `Set#has` is broken for fresh coords *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** D3 locks `static.walls: Set<Coord>` and `static.targets: Set<Coord>`. ES
+`Set` uses SameValueZero, which for objects is referential equality. A box pushed onto a
+target is a *fresh* `Coord` (`{ x: bx + dx, y: by + dy }`), so
+`state.static.targets.has(freshBox)` returns `false` even when the box is structurally on a
+target — `winCheck` would never report a win. Likewise `walls.has(next)` for a freshly
+computed `next` coord: the wall `Coord` objects were created by the level loader, the
+player's `next` is freshly computed — different references, `false` negative, the player
+would walk through walls.
+
+**How the design avoids it.** `coordKey(c: Coord): string` returns `"${c.x},${c.y}"`. Both
+`move` and `winCheck` build a local `Set<string>` from `state.static.walls` / `.targets`
+once per call and test `coordKey(candidate)` against it. `static` itself is never mutated
+and stays a `Set<Coord>` (D3 lock intact). Cost: O(W) ≤ ~225 + O(T) ≤ ~30 per move —
+nanoseconds. **Mitigation confidence: HIGH.**
+
+**Test coverage.** Test #7 (all boxes on targets → `won: true`) and test #23 (push last
+box onto target → `won: true`) both rely on this path; if `coordKey` were missing they
+would fail, making the trap surface in RED.
+
+### P2: `noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true` — `boxes[i]` is `Coord | undefined` *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** `tsconfig.json` has `noUncheckedIndexedAccess: true`. Every `arr[i]` read is
+`T | undefined`. Affected sites: `state.boxes[boxIndex]` in `move.ts`; the undo-restore
+`boxes.map((b, i) => i === idx ? from : b)` is fine (no index read), but
+`state.history[state.history.length - 1]` in `popEntry` is `HistoryEntry | undefined`.
+
+**How the design avoids it.** Explicit `undefined` guards after every indexed read, even
+when the index is provably valid (e.g. `findIndex` → `boxIndex`):
+```ts
+const boxFrom = state.boxes[boxIndex];
+if (boxFrom === undefined) return null;
+```
+This satisfies the compiler without `!` non-null assertions (which would hide a genuine
+future regression if `boxIndex` ever became stale). For array *updates*, the design uses
+`.slice()` + index assignment (`newBoxes[boxIndex] = beyond`) — assignment to a known index
+is allowed under `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` (it only narrows *reads*), but reads back
+immediately after would still be `| undefined`; the design avoids read-back. **Mitigation
+confidence: HIGH.**
+
+### P3: `static` referential equality — must be reused by reference, never mutated *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** D3 / architecture: `static` is derived once from the `Level` and reused by
+reference across every reducer output. If any code mutates `static.walls` or
+`static.targets`, every historical `GameState` in the undo stack is corrupted (they all
+share the same `static`). This is the architecture's stated Risk: "Set<Coord> mutation when
+sharing state.static".
+
+**How the design avoids it.** `move` and `winCheck` only *read* `static` (iterating to
+build a local `Set<string>`); they never call `.add`/`.delete`/`.clear` on `static.walls`
+or `static.targets`. The reducer's spread (`{ ...moved }`, `{ ...cleared }`, `{ ...state }`)
+copies the `static` *reference*, not the object. `createInitialState` is the single place
+that constructs `static`, from the `Level`, once.
+
+**Test coverage.** Test #25 runs N=5 moves and asserts `state.static === initialState.static`
+(referential equality). This catches any accidental copy or mutation. **Mitigation
+confidence: HIGH.**
+
+### P4: Animation `duration` — constant vs. config *(MEDIUM)*
+
+**The trap.** D8 defines `AnimSpec.duration` but does not say where the value comes from.
+Hardcoding a bare `120` in the reducer couples ph.2 to a magic number; building a config
+system in ph.2 is over-engineering (no config exists yet).
+
+**How the design avoids it.** Export `MOVE_DURATION_MS = 120` from `reducer.ts`. Tests
+import it and assert `anim.duration === MOVE_DURATION_MS` (no magic number in tests). ph.5
+imports the same constant for the animator. ph.9 may lift it to a config if tuning is
+needed. The value 120 ms is within the NFR-5 100–150 ms band. **Mitigation confidence:
+HIGH on the mechanism (exported constant); MEDIUM on the exact value (ph.5 may tune).**
+
+### P5: `AnimSpec` push semantics — single `from`/`to` for two moving entities *(MEDIUM)*
+
+**The trap.** D8 locks `AnimSpec = { from, to, duration, entities: ('player' | number)[] }`.
+A push moves the player (A→B) and the box (B→C) along different segments, but the shape has
+only one `from`/`to`. A naive reading would animate both entities over the same segment.
+
+**How the design avoids it.** Interpret `from`/`to` as the **player's** previous→current
+coords. Every entity in `entities` translates by the shared move delta `delta = to − from`
+(which equals the direction vector). For a push, the box's visual segment is
+`[boxLogicalOld, boxLogicalOld + delta]` = `[B, C]`, and the player's is `[A, B]` = `[from,
+to]`. The ph.5 animator, which has access to each entity's committed logical position (and
+a one-step previous-position lag via `HistoryEntry`), derives each segment from the shared
+delta. This keeps the locked shape intact and is internally consistent. **Mitigation
+confidence: MEDIUM** — the interpretation is sound, but ph.5 is the consumer that confirms
+it; if ph.5 finds the shared-delta derivation awkward, the alternative is a per-entity
+`from`/`to` map, which would require a context amendment (documented in Alternatives).
+
+### P6: Pure 2-arg `reducer` needs an initial-state reference for `reset` *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** The assignment pins `reducer(state, intent): { state; anim? }` — a 2-arg
+pure function. `reset` must rebuild the initial state, but a pure 2-arg function has no
+closure over the `Level` or `initialState`. Options: (a) a `createReducer` factory
+(changes the export shape), (b) carry `initial` on `GameState` (extends D3), (c) embed
+initial positions in `static` (misleading grouping).
+
+**How the design avoids it.** Option (b): `GameState.initial = { player, boxes }`, set
+once by `createInitialState`, immutable, shared by reference across all reducer outputs
+(never copied except `boxes.slice()` at reset). The reducer's `reset` branch reads
+`state.initial` and produces a fresh state with `history: []`, `moveCount: 0`,
+`player: initial.player`, `boxes: initial.boxes.slice()`. `initial` carries no per-move
+allocation cost (spread copies the reference). **Mitigation confidence: HIGH** that an
+initial reference is required; **MEDIUM** on the field location (top-level `initial` is
+recommended; the planner may prefer a factory — see Alternatives).
+
+### P7: Undo must restore BOTH player and box, and recompute `won` (BLOCKER #3, #17) *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** Pitfalls #3 (BLOCKER): undo that only restores the player leaves the pushed
+box displaced. #17 (MAJOR): reset that does not clear the undo stack lets the player rewind
+into pre-reset history. Both are correctness, not polish.
+
+**How the design avoids it.** `HistoryEntry` carries `pushedBoxIndex` + `boxFrom` for
+pushes; the reducer's `undo` branch restores `boxes[pushedBoxIndex] = boxFrom` via
+`.map()` (immutable) AND `player = entry.player` AND `moveCount = entry.moveCount`, then
+recomputes `won = winCheck(restored)`. `reset` calls `clearHistory(state)` first, so
+post-reset undo is a no-op (empty stack). `won` is recomputed on move, undo, AND reset
+(D4). **Mitigation confidence: HIGH.**
+
+**Test coverage.** Test #19 (undo of push restores both), #20 (undo on empty stack =
+no-op), #22 (reset then undo = no-op), #24 (win → undo → `won: false`).
+
+### P8: `verbatimModuleSyntax: true` — type-only imports must use `import type` *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** `verbatimModuleSyntax` errors on `import { Coord } from '../types'` when
+`Coord` is used only as a type — it must be `import type { Coord } from '../types'`. Mixed
+value+type imports need `import { move } from './move'` + a separate
+`import type { Coord } from '../types'`.
+
+**How the design avoids it.** Every signature above uses `import type` for type-only
+specifiers (`Coord`, `Direction`, `GameState`, `HistoryEntry`, `AnimSpec`, `Intent`,
+`Level`, `MoveResult`) and a plain `import` for runtime values (`move`, `winCheck`,
+`pushEntry`, `popEntry`, `clearHistory`, `coordKey`). **Mitigation confidence: HIGH.**
+
+### P9: Invalid move must return the SAME reference, not a clone (D7) *(HIGH)*
+
+**The trap.** A naive reducer might return `{ ...state }` on an invalid move "for
+consistency" — breaking the `===` contract callers rely on (D7) and allocating gratuitously.
+
+**How the design avoids it.** `move` returns `null` for invalid; the reducer's `move` branch
+returns `{ state }` (the original reference, no spread) when `result === null`. Same for
+`undo` on an empty stack. **Mitigation confidence: HIGH.**
+
+**Test coverage.** Test #17 (`expect(result.state).toBe(originalState)`) and #20.
+
+---
+
+## TDD Implications
+
+- **All tests RED first.** Write each test, run `npm test`, watch it fail for the right
+  reason (import-not-found or assertion mismatch), then implement until GREEN, then
+  REFACTOR. No implementation file is written before its first failing test.
+- **Pure logic only.** No DOM, no mocks, no fake clock (anim is a data value, not a tween).
+  Tests run under the `unit` Vitest project (node env) — confirmed by `vitest.config.ts`.
+- **Fast.** Target: full `tests/unit/core/` suite < 50 ms. No I/O, no async, no DOM.
+- **Per-test inline fixtures.** Each test constructs a `Level` inline (small `Set<Coord>`
+  walls/targets, a player, boxes) and calls `createInitialState(level)`. No shared fixture
+  file (D10). A tiny `makeLevel()` test helper local to each file is acceptable; do NOT
+  create a shared `tests/unit/core/fixtures.ts` in ph.2 (defer to ph.3 with the loader).
+- **Test count target: ≥ 12.** The list below has 25 tests — well above the bar. The
+  executor may prune to ~15 if RED→GREEN velocity demands, but the BLOCKER-coverage tests
+  (#19, #20, #22, #23, #24, #25) are mandatory.
+- **`expect.toBe` for referential equality** (invalid move, empty-stack undo, `static`
+  invariance); `toEqual` for structural equality of new states.
+
+---
+
+## Test List (GIVEN / WHEN / THEN)
+
+Test files live in `tests/unit/core/`. Organized by module. 25 tests total; minimum 12
+required.
+
+### `tests/unit/core/move.test.ts` — `move` helper (6 tests)
+
+1. **move into floor**
+   - GIVEN a state with player at `{2,2}`, no box at `{2,1}`, no wall at `{2,1}`
+   - WHEN `move(state, 'N')`
+   - THEN returns `{ player: {2,1}, boxes: <same ref> }` with no `pushedIndex`/`boxFrom`.
+
+2. **move into wall**
+   - GIVEN a state with a wall at `{2,1}` (in `static.walls`)
+   - WHEN `move(state, 'N')`
+   - THEN returns `null`.
+
+3. **push box onto floor**
+   - GIVEN player at `{2,2}`, box at `{2,1}`, floor at `{2,0}`
+   - WHEN `move(state, 'N')`
+   - THEN returns `{ player: {2,1}, boxes: [{2,0}], pushedIndex: 0, boxFrom: {2,1} }`.
+
+4. **push box blocked by wall**
+   - GIVEN player at `{2,2}`, box at `{2,1}`, wall at `{2,0}`
+   - WHEN `move(state, 'N')`
+   - THEN returns `null` (neither player nor box moves).
+
+5. **push box blocked by another box**
+   - GIVEN player at `{2,2}`, box0 at `{2,1}`, box1 at `{2,0}`
+   - WHEN `move(state, 'N')`
+   - THEN returns `null` (cannot push two boxes).
+
+6. **push box onto target succeeds** (move does not treat target specially)
+   - GIVEN player at `{2,2}`, box at `{2,1}`, target at `{2,0}` (and no wall)
+   - WHEN `move(state, 'N')`
+   - THEN returns a push result with `boxes: [{2,0}]` (validity is walls/boxes only).
+
+### `tests/unit/core/winCheck.test.ts` — `winCheck` (4 tests)
+
+7. **all boxes on targets → true** (exercises `coordKey` path)
+   - GIVEN a state with `boxes = [{1,1},{3,3}]` and `targets = {{1,1},{3,3}}` (same
+     structure, different object refs)
+   - WHEN `winCheck(state)`
+   - THEN returns `true`.
+
+8. **one box off target → false**
+   - GIVEN `boxes = [{1,1},{3,3}]`, `targets = {{1,1},{5,5}}`
+   - WHEN `winCheck(state)`
+   - THEN returns `false`.
+
+9. **box count ≠ target count → false**
+   - GIVEN `boxes = [{1,1}]`, `targets = {{1,1},{3,3}}` (count mismatch)
+   - WHEN `winCheck(state)`
+   - THEN returns `false`.
+
+10. **empty boxes and empty targets → true** (degenerate but defined)
+    - GIVEN `boxes = []`, `targets = {}` (size 0)
+    - WHEN `winCheck(state)`
+    - THEN returns `true`.
+
+### `tests/unit/core/history.test.ts` — stack helpers (4 tests)
+
+11. **pushEntry is immutable and appends**
+    - GIVEN a state with `history = [e0]`
+    - WHEN `pushEntry(state, e1)`
+    - THEN returns a NEW state with `history = [e0, e1]` AND the original `state.history`
+      is still `[e0]` (no mutation).
+
+12. **popEntry on non-empty returns entry + shortened state**
+    - GIVEN `history = [e0, e1]`
+    - WHEN `popEntry(state)`
+    - THEN returns `{ state: { history: [e0] }, entry: e1 }`.
+
+13. **popEntry on empty returns null**
+    - GIVEN `history = []`
+    - WHEN `popEntry(state)`
+    - THEN returns `null`.
+
+14. **clearHistory empties the stack**
+    - GIVEN `history = [e0, e1, e2]`
+    - WHEN `clearHistory(state)`
+    - THEN returns a NEW state with `history = []`.
+
+### `tests/unit/core/reducer.test.ts` — reducer integration (11 tests)
+
+15. **reducer walk: state advances, anim emitted, no push**
+    - GIVEN initial state (player `{2,2}`, floor `{2,1}`)
+    - WHEN `reducer(state, { type: 'move', dir: 'N' })`
+    - THEN `result.state.player === {2,1}`, `moveCount === 1`, `history.length === 1`,
+      `result.anim.entities === ['player']`, `result.anim.duration === MOVE_DURATION_MS`,
+      `result.anim.from === {2,2}`, `result.anim.to === {2,1}`, `won === false`.
+
+16. **reducer push: box moves, anim lists box index**
+    - GIVEN player `{2,2}`, box0 at `{2,1}`, floor `{2,0}`
+    - WHEN `reducer(state, { type: 'move', dir: 'N' })`
+    - THEN `result.state.boxes[0] === {2,0}`, `result.anim.entities === ['player', 0]`,
+      `history.length === 1`, `moveCount === 1`.
+
+17. **reducer invalid move returns same reference, no anim** (D7)
+    - GIVEN player `{2,2}`, wall at `{2,1}`
+    - WHEN `const r = reducer(state, { type: 'move', dir: 'N' })`
+    - THEN `r.state === state` (referential), `r.anim === undefined`.
+
+18. **reducer undo of walk restores player + moveCount, no anim**
+    - GIVEN state after one walk (`moveCount 1`, `history.length 1`)
+    - WHEN `reducer(state, { type: 'undo' })`
+    - THEN `result.state.player === initial.player`, `moveCount === 0`,
+      `history.length === 0`, `result.anim === undefined`.
+
+19. **reducer undo of push restores player AND box** (BLOCKER #3)
+    - GIVEN state after one push (box0 moved `{2,1}`→`{2,0}`, player `{2,2}`→`{2,1}`)
+    - WHEN `reducer(state, { type: 'undo' })`
+    - THEN `result.state.player === {2,2}`, `result.state.boxes[0] === {2,1}`,
+      `moveCount === 0`.
+
+20. **reducer undo on empty stack is a no-op (same ref)** (BLOCKER #3 edge)
+    - GIVEN fresh state (`history.length 0`)
+    - WHEN `const r = reducer(state, { type: 'undo' })`
+    - THEN `r.state === state`, `r.anim === undefined`.
+
+21. **reducer reset restores initial positions, moveCount 0, history cleared**
+    - GIVEN state after several moves (player and boxes moved, `moveCount 3`,
+      `history.length 3`)
+    - WHEN `reducer(state, { type: 'reset' })`
+    - THEN `result.state.player === initial.player`, `result.state.boxes` deep-equals
+      `initial.boxes`, `moveCount === 0`, `history.length === 0`, `result.anim === undefined`.
+
+22. **reset clears the undo stack — reset then undo is a no-op** (MAJOR #17)
+    - GIVEN state after several moves
+    - WHEN `reducer(state, { type: 'reset' })` then `reducer(resetState, { type: 'undo' })`
+    - THEN the second call returns `resetState` by reference (`===`), no anim — cannot
+      rewind into pre-reset history.
+
+23. **win detection: push last box onto target → `won: true`**
+    - GIVEN a level with one box already on its target and one box off-target, player
+      positioned to push the off-target box onto the last free target
+    - WHEN the winning push move is dispatched
+    - THEN `result.state.won === true`.
+
+24. **win recomputed on undo: win → undo → `won: false`** (BLOCKER #3 / D4)
+    - GIVEN a `won: true` state from test #23
+    - WHEN `reducer(wonState, { type: 'undo' })`
+    - THEN `result.state.won === false` (the undone push removed a box from its target).
+
+25. **`static` referential equality across N moves** (architecture Risk / P3)
+    - GIVEN an initial state
+    - WHEN 5 successive walk moves are dispatched (a sequence that does not hit walls)
+    - THEN every intermediate `result.state.static === initialState.static` (same
+      reference; `static` never copied or mutated).
+
